<bill id="DLM1826700" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" xml:lang="en-NZ" year.imprint="2009" bill.no="12" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
  <billdetail>
    <title>Sentencing (Offender Levy) Amendment Bill</title>
    <billtype>Government Bill</billtype>
    <repnote>As reported from the Justice and Electoral Committee</repnote>
    <commentary id="DLM2251000" in.amend="false" irdnumbering="no" official="yes" bill.no="12" bill.type="government" stage="2" year="2009">
      <heading>Commentary</heading>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Recommendation</heading>
        <para>
          <text>The Justice and Electoral Committee has examined the Sentencing (Offender Levy) Amendment Bill and recommends that it be passed with the amendments shown.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Introduction</heading>
        <para>
          <text>This bill principally amends the Sentencing Act 2002. It proposes to impose a $50 levy on all convicted offenders when they are sentenced or otherwise dealt with by either the District or High Courts. Revenue generated from the levy would be used to fund new entitlements and services for victims of serious crime.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Offender required to pay levy</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We heard evidence on new section 105B, which provides that all offenders convicted of an offence must pay the levy when they are sentenced or otherwise dealt with by a court and that this levy is in addition to any other sentence that might be imposed by the criminal courts. While we do not recommend any amendments to new section 105B, we examined the possibility of two amendments in detail before deciding against them.</text>
        </para>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Imposing the levy for each offence</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We considered whether the levy could be imposed for each offence for which an offender had been convicted, rather than for each sentencing event as specified in the bill as introduced. We consider that requiring the levy to be paid for each offence could create financial difficulties for many offenders, who might then fail to pay, which would undermine the purpose of the levy. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Excluding young offenders from offender levy scheme</heading>
          <para>
            <text>We considered whether all young offenders, or young offenders who had been initially convicted in the Youth Court then transferred to the District Court, could be specifically excluded from the requirement to pay the levy. </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Under new section 105B of the bill as introduced, the levy will apply to only those young offenders convicted in the Youth Court under section 283(o) of the Children, Young Persons, and Their Families Act 1989 and transferred to the District Court for sentencing or decision. We were informed that each year approximately 270 young offenders are convicted in the Youth Court and then transferred to the District Court, therefore the majority of young offenders would be exempt from paying the levy.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>While we consider that there is some merit to excluding young offenders from the offender levy, we do not recommend amending the bill as it would increase the associated administrative costs.</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Amount of the levy</heading>
        <para>
          <text>New section 105D sets the amount of the levy at $50. A number of submitters were concerned that this might not be sufficient to draw to the offender’s attention the seriousness of the impact of the crime on the offender’s victims and could result in financial difficulties for offenders. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We do not recommend that the amount of the levy be altered. We consider that setting the levy at $50 would minimise the potential for financial hardship to be caused to offenders and maximise collection rates. We also note that clause 9 of the bill as introduced would allow the amount of the levy to be changed by Order in Council. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We also considered whether the flat rate of the levy was fair, as serious and minor offences would incur the same levy. We concluded that consideration of the seriousness of the offence occurs in sentencing; the underlying purpose of the levy is to ensure that offenders contribute to addressing the harm that they cause to victims.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Approval of agency</heading>
        <para>
          <text>New section 105J sets out the process that the Secretary of Justice must follow for approval of organisations as approved agencies for the purposes of providing victims with services paid for from the victims’ services bank account. We recommend amending new section 105J to replace references to <quote.in quote="1">support</quote.in> to victims of crime, with <quote.in quote="1">services</quote.in> to victims of crime. This reflects more accurately the purpose of approved agencies, which would be to provide specific entitlements and services.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Sale of confiscated motor vehicles</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend amending section 137 of the Sentencing Act to include a reference to the levy payable under new section 105B of the bill as introduced. Section 137 of the Sentencing Act provides that any fines, reparations, and court costs owed by the offender are to be paid from the proceeds of the sale of the offender’s confiscated motor vehicle. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>Consequential amendments to other enactments</heading>
        <para>
          <text>We recommend replacing clause 10 with new clause 10, which would insert a new schedule to address consequential amendments to other enactments. We note that clause 10 of the bill as introduced amends the Social Security Act 1964 to include a reference to the offender levy in the definition of <quote.in quote="1">fine</quote.in> in section 126A(1) of the Social Security Act 1964.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We are aware that a similar definition of <quote.in quote="1">fine</quote.in> is found in the Tax Administration Act 1994, the Customs and Excise Act 1996, and the Immigration Act 1987. We recommend that new clause 10 amend the definition of <quote.in quote="1">fine</quote.in> provided in these three Acts to include a reference to the offender levy. This would allow those owing the offender levy to be matched in the authorised information programmes conducted by the Ministry of Justice. </text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We note that sections 81 and 83 of the Summary Proceedings Act 1957 provide that when the Court is ordering a defendant to pay a fine, the order can require immediate payment or allow payment by instalments. The effect of these sections would be inconsistent with the priority of payments specified in new section 105C of the bill as introduced. We recommend that new clause 10 also amend sections 81 and 83 of the Summary Proceedings Act to ensure that the priority of payments to be received from an offender would not be altered by a section 81 or 83 order from the Court.</text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.lev1>
        <heading>New Zealand Labour view</heading>
        <para>
          <text>Labour members of the committee support increased funding for victims of serious crime, and on this basis support the bill, but with reservations.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We note that funding for the scheme is at the cost of the disestablishment of the Sentencing Council, which would have improved the Justice System by delivering consistency with sentencing.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>Further, we remain concerned about the high administration costs of the scheme and the possibility that the levy could detrimentally affect reparation payments.</text>
        </para>
        <para>
          <text>We intend to closely monitor the effectiveness of the scheme. </text>
        </para>
      </comm.lev1>
      <comm.appendix>
        <heading>Appendix</heading>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee process</heading>
          <para>
            <text>The Sentencing (Offender Levy) Amendment Bill was referred to us on 12 February 2009. The closing date for submissions was 6 April 2009. We received and considered 13 submissions from interested groups and individuals. We heard seven submissions.</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>We received advice from the Ministry of Justice. </text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
        <comm.lev2>
          <heading>Committee membership</heading>
          <para>
            <text>Chester Borrows (Chairperson)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Jacinda Ardern </text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Kanwaljit Singh Bakshi</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Simon Bridges</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Dr Kennedy Graham</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon Nathan Guy (from 24 June 2009)</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Hon David Parker</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Lynne Pillay</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Paul Quinn</text>
          </para>
          <para>
            <text>Dr Richard Worth (until 16 June 2009)</text>
          </para>
        </comm.lev2>
      </comm.appendix>
    </commentary>
  </billdetail>
